    <title>Unexpected curves arising from special line arrangements</title>
    <summary>  In a recent paper arXiv:1602.02300v2, Cook II, Harbourne, Migliore and Nagel
related the splitting type of a line arrangement in the projective plane to the
number of conditions imposed by a general fat point of multiplicity $j$ to the
linear system of curves of degree $j+1$ passing through the configuration of
points dual to the given arrangement. If the number of conditions is less than
the expected, we say that the configuration of points admits unexpected curves.
In this paper, we characterize supersolvable line arrangements whose dual
configuration admits unexpected curves and we provide other infinite families
of line arrangements with this property.
</summary>
